WEBVTT

00:01.000 --> 00:02.836
LINDA TANNER: Wall Street Journal
is doing an article.

00:02.836 --> 00:04.838
I don't think it's going to be positive.

00:04.838 --> 00:06.673
- Does Schultz know
his grandson is talking to us?

00:06.673 --> 00:08.425
- Did you speak to the reporter?

00:08.425 --> 00:10.469
- No.
- Here's the restraining order.

00:10.469 --> 00:12.763
We're preparing to file
a lawsuit against you.

00:12.763 --> 00:14.348
JOHN CARREYROU:
I am a little bit worried

00:14.348 --> 00:16.350
they're going to come
after my sources.

00:16.350 --> 00:17.518
[gasping]
- Oh my god.

00:17.518 --> 00:19.978
TYLER SCHULTZ: It's bad right now.
They're suing me.

00:19.978 --> 00:22.481
They're tracking everything I do.

00:22.481 --> 00:24.149
- You haven't heard from Tyler?

00:24.149 --> 00:26.610
- No. But that also means
I haven't heard that he's recanted.

00:27.152 --> 00:29.613
- Elizabeth, they're running it.

00:29.613 --> 00:32.406
ELIZABETH HOLMES: I don't know
what I'm supposed to fucking do.

00:32.406 --> 00:33.867
You should have protected me.

00:33.867 --> 00:35.994
- I think it might be time
to consider

00:35.994 --> 00:38.539
whether you have
the right people around you.

00:43.919 --> 00:46.338
LAWYER: So if you look
at the third text message

00:46.338 --> 00:49.132
down at 7:26 p.m.
from Mr. Balwani,

00:49.132 --> 00:52.386
he says, "Okay, WAG freaking out.

00:52.386 --> 00:53.762
Lack of transparency."

00:54.680 --> 00:56.265
You see that?
- Yes.

00:56.932 --> 00:58.809
LAWYER: And you understand
"WAG" is Walgreens?

00:59.935 --> 01:00.811
- Yes.

01:01.478 --> 01:03.730
LAWYER: What did you understand him
to be referring to here?

01:06.024 --> 01:06.942
- I--

01:09.194 --> 01:10.195
I don't know.

01:12.948 --> 01:15.742
I don't remember
text exchanges with Sunny

01:15.742 --> 01:17.286
from years ago.

01:18.036 --> 01:20.956
LAWYER: Do you remember
discussing with Mr. Balwani

01:20.956 --> 01:24.626
the concerns Walgreens had
following Mr. Carreyrou's article?

01:25.502 --> 01:26.545
- Um...

01:28.714 --> 01:30.174
I'm just thinking back.

01:31.508 --> 01:34.011
♪ upbeat percussive music ♪

01:41.685 --> 01:42.519
[slurps]

01:43.061 --> 01:44.271
[sighs]

01:45.397 --> 01:46.398
[sighs]

01:47.107 --> 01:50.986
♪

01:57.993 --> 01:59.786
- Hi, this is Elizabeth Holmes.

01:59.786 --> 02:00.662
How are you?

02:01.371 --> 02:02.998
Th-that's why I'm calling.

02:02.998 --> 02:05.501
You may have seen a recent piece

02:05.501 --> 02:07.586
about Theranos
in The Wall Street Journal.

02:07.586 --> 02:10.172
First and foremost, I, I just want
to make sure that you know

02:10.172 --> 02:13.008
that everything that they have
written about us is false.

02:13.008 --> 02:15.219
You're such a valued member
of our board,

02:15.219 --> 02:18.305
and, uh, I wanted you
to hear it from me.

02:18.847 --> 02:20.182
Well, it's sexism.

02:20.599 --> 02:22.851
Yeah, this reporter clearly has
an issue with women.

02:23.352 --> 02:24.520
Yeah. Women in power.

02:24.937 --> 02:26.897
That's right. John Carreyrou.

02:28.440 --> 02:30.859
R-O-U. Yeah, apparently
he was born in France.

02:30.859 --> 02:32.528
SUNNY BALWANI:
Wade, it's Sunny again.

02:32.528 --> 02:34.029
Look, I, I know you're unhappy,

02:34.029 --> 02:36.532
but the fact is the story is bullshit.

02:36.532 --> 02:37.866
- And because of his sexist reporting,

02:37.866 --> 02:40.452
I'm, I'm now the target
for all sorts of harassment.

02:40.452 --> 02:44.248
- Jay, if you will call me back,
I will happily explain in more detail.

02:44.248 --> 02:46.500
- Yeah, you, you wouldn't believe
the kinds of messages

02:46.500 --> 02:49.253
that I've been receiving on social media.

02:49.253 --> 02:50.254
- Cocksucker!

02:50.254 --> 02:52.548
ELIZABETH:
Death threats, sexual, perverse.

02:52.548 --> 02:55.759
I've had to put bulletproof glass
on my office windows.

02:55.759 --> 02:57.094
Yeah, like the White House.

02:57.845 --> 03:00.013
Yes, a woman does belong there.

03:00.013 --> 03:02.015
Well, you know me.
I'm a fighter.

03:02.015 --> 03:04.142
And I-I've actually been promoting
a hashtag on Twitter.

03:04.142 --> 03:05.477
Iron Sisters.

03:05.477 --> 03:08.605
Amelia Earhart.
Margaret Thatcher.

03:08.605 --> 03:10.065
Other great women in history

03:10.065 --> 03:13.193
who faced tremendous resistance
in their time.

03:13.193 --> 03:15.571
Marie Curie, Rosa Parks--
SUNNY: Dr. J.

03:15.571 --> 03:17.823
Hi, it's Sunny Balwani
trying you again--

03:17.823 --> 03:20.158
- We knew there were problems
with the nanotainer.

03:20.158 --> 03:22.077
That's, that's why we pulled it.

03:22.077 --> 03:24.705
We are ahead of it.
Our labs are still running.

03:24.705 --> 03:25.956
We're containing the problem.

03:25.956 --> 03:29.543
The biggest challenges create
the biggest opportunities.

03:29.543 --> 03:32.546
Yeah, it's kind of like an ocean.
Big waves, they come and they go.

03:32.546 --> 03:34.631
But there's a reason
that you're still there.

03:34.631 --> 03:36.633
Obviously, you're
the kind of guy who gets it--

03:36.633 --> 03:37.843
Obviously, you're the kind
of guy who gets it--

03:37.843 --> 03:39.219
Obviously, you're
the kind of guy who gets it--

03:39.219 --> 03:42.139
Henry, I consider you an ally of, of me.

03:43.182 --> 03:44.433
Of women as a whole.

03:45.392 --> 03:47.477
I'm, I'm, I'm so glad to hear it.

03:47.477 --> 03:49.354
I can't tell you how much it means
to me to have your support--

03:49.354 --> 03:50.272
It means the world to me--

03:50.272 --> 03:51.690
Thank you so much.

03:51.690 --> 03:52.941
Take care. Bye.

03:53.984 --> 03:55.652
Mattis is still with us.

03:55.652 --> 03:57.487
- That's the whole board, isn't it?
ELIZABETH: It is.

03:58.780 --> 03:59.823
What about Carreyrou?

04:00.616 --> 04:01.783
- We're workin' on it.

04:02.868 --> 04:04.369
JOHN:
Everything?

04:04.369 --> 04:06.496
Just everything
on my computer gets copied

04:06.496 --> 04:08.540
and preserved forever
by The Journal?

04:08.540 --> 04:11.668
- They're strongly advising us
to be prepared for a defamation lawsuit.

04:11.668 --> 04:13.962
This is what prepared looks like.

04:13.962 --> 04:15.714
- You know what they're doing, right?

04:15.714 --> 04:17.674
They protect themselves
with NDAs, right,

04:17.674 --> 04:19.593
and then they go out
and terrorize people.

04:19.593 --> 04:20.761
They've been following me for months.

04:20.761 --> 04:22.804
- John--
- Boies is getting away with it. He is.

04:22.804 --> 04:23.972
She is getting away with it.

04:23.972 --> 04:26.517
She hasn't lost a single member
of her board.

04:26.517 --> 04:28.060
She called me a misogynist in public.

04:28.060 --> 04:31.063
I mean, she is stalling
until people forget.

04:31.063 --> 04:34.358
She's stalling because she knows
that people are going to forget.

04:34.358 --> 04:36.276
- Are you going
to give me another speech

04:36.276 --> 04:38.529
on the relentless speed
of the modern American news cycle.

04:38.529 --> 04:41.198
- Donald Trump called McCain a loser,
and no one cares.

04:41.198 --> 04:43.325
- This is the battleground, John.

04:44.409 --> 04:46.870
And the best way to keep
the pressure on Theranos

04:46.870 --> 04:49.831
is to keep making news, and the best way
to keep making news,

04:49.831 --> 04:51.667
and I hope this doesn't come
as a shock,

04:51.667 --> 04:53.961
is to tell the people something new.

04:55.212 --> 04:57.339
Go to Tyler and make him
go on the record.

04:58.215 --> 05:00.467
And then the story becomes
about George Schultz.

05:00.467 --> 05:02.052
And then we have more news, right?

05:03.428 --> 05:04.263
Right.

05:05.973 --> 05:08.767
- That was the kind of pep talk I've been
waiting years for you to give.

05:14.106 --> 05:15.190
[sighs]
Okay!

05:16.108 --> 05:17.401
Who's got an extra computer?

05:22.990 --> 05:24.992
SUNNY:
Yeah. Yeah.

05:28.036 --> 05:29.288
Thanks for calling me back.

05:30.706 --> 05:31.999
It's not a good time to talk.

05:40.048 --> 05:41.049
I know.

05:45.304 --> 05:46.305
Yeah.

05:50.934 --> 05:53.228
I want to discuss
what my options are,

05:53.228 --> 05:56.732
get your perspective
on what my exposure is.

06:00.611 --> 06:02.362
[door creaking]

06:07.534 --> 06:09.244
You know, I'll call you back another time.

06:10.913 --> 06:11.914
Goodbye.

06:14.583 --> 06:15.751
Baby, are you there?

06:20.005 --> 06:21.423
ELIZABETH:
Yeah, I'm just heading home.

06:23.592 --> 06:25.219
SUNNY:
I have some things to finish.

06:26.929 --> 06:27.971
I'll meet you there.

06:30.098 --> 06:34.311
♪ tense music playing ♪

06:34.311 --> 06:37.356
♪

06:42.945 --> 06:44.613
TYLER:
Look, she's fooled lots of people.

06:44.613 --> 06:46.365
I don't get why CMS
would be any different.

06:46.365 --> 06:48.408
- The articles aren't enough.
Alright?

06:48.408 --> 06:49.743
She's still running her labs.

06:49.743 --> 06:51.411
She's still sending bad results
to people.

06:51.411 --> 06:52.412
- I know--
ERIKA: Fuck this.

06:52.412 --> 06:55.541
No, fuck everything, I'm going
to send that motherfucking letter!

06:55.541 --> 06:58.001
TYLER: To some obscure government agency
that no one's ever heard of?

06:58.001 --> 06:58.919
- C-M-fucking-S.

06:58.919 --> 07:01.296
- You're swearing a lot. I like it.
I'm just pointing it out.

07:01.296 --> 07:02.422
[exhales]

07:03.298 --> 07:06.301
What is CMS going to do that
The Wall Street Journal can't do?

07:06.718 --> 07:08.303
- Does CMS excite you?

07:09.221 --> 07:12.432
Okay, does it get you
all, uh, hot and thirsty?

07:13.141 --> 07:14.268
- I don't know how to answer that.

07:14.268 --> 07:16.854
- No, it doesn't.
Because it's boring.

07:16.854 --> 07:18.522
My god, even the name's boring.

07:18.522 --> 07:21.358
Center for Medicare
and Medicaid Services.

07:21.358 --> 07:22.651
It-it's just, like, so boring

07:22.651 --> 07:23.944
that I can't even say it
without being bored.

07:23.944 --> 07:26.905
And Elizabeth, no,
she can't spin boring.

07:26.905 --> 07:29.491
Underfunded and understaffed,
but if they get a formal complaint,

07:29.491 --> 07:30.742
they have to investigate it.

07:30.742 --> 07:32.828
It's just this fucking boring

07:32.828 --> 07:35.372
fucking federal fucking regulatory agency

07:35.372 --> 07:36.665
that can shut her ass down.

07:39.418 --> 07:42.296
♪

07:42.296 --> 07:43.630
- You signed your name?

07:44.256 --> 07:45.257
- Yeah, I know.

07:47.926 --> 07:48.969
- Are-are you sure?

07:48.969 --> 07:50.387
- No.

07:52.598 --> 07:53.640
But I'm doing it.

07:55.684 --> 07:57.519
Like, I, I want there
to be a record.

07:58.645 --> 08:00.397
And I want people to remember
what she did,

08:00.397 --> 08:03.233
and I want it down on paper
and I want to sign my name.

08:03.233 --> 08:05.235
♪

08:07.696 --> 08:08.906
Do you think it's dumb?

08:15.579 --> 08:18.832
- No. I think it's fucking amazing.

08:25.923 --> 08:27.549
GEORGE SCHULTZ:
Charlotte tells me

08:27.549 --> 08:29.676
you have something
you'd like to say.

08:31.178 --> 08:32.721
Yeah, I, uh...

08:33.514 --> 08:35.140
I, I wrote it down.

08:37.643 --> 08:40.521
And I'm...
I'm just going to read it.

08:49.613 --> 08:50.697
[exhales]

08:58.080 --> 08:59.081
Grandpa.

09:00.499 --> 09:02.793
Before I explain everything,

09:02.793 --> 09:05.337
I think it's important
that I tell you the truth.

09:05.337 --> 09:07.506
- That you are
the reporter's source.

09:07.506 --> 09:10.092
- George.
- You've been his source all along.

09:11.718 --> 09:12.761
Just say it.

09:15.973 --> 09:17.558
[inhales sharply]

09:20.936 --> 09:23.605
- I was the one who talked
to the reporter from The Wall Street--

09:23.605 --> 09:24.857
- I trusted you.

09:26.358 --> 09:28.068
I asked you not to lie.

09:29.319 --> 09:31.530
And you lied to me.

09:37.202 --> 09:39.872
- And I am now planning
to go on the record

09:39.872 --> 09:41.540
for a future article.

09:41.540 --> 09:42.875
- Excuse me?

09:44.418 --> 09:45.961
I'm going
to let John use my name.

09:48.422 --> 09:49.590
- Your name?

09:50.757 --> 09:52.009
You mean my name?

09:54.261 --> 09:56.346
- It's my name, too.
- You go on the record

09:56.930 --> 09:58.724
and this story becomes about me.

09:59.266 --> 10:00.684
You understand that, right?

10:01.685 --> 10:02.686
Do you understand

10:03.645 --> 10:05.439
what my name means to people?

10:05.439 --> 10:06.523
- Yes!

10:08.483 --> 10:10.694
Your name has been my whole life.

10:10.694 --> 10:12.112
- And that makes you angry?

10:14.323 --> 10:15.282
Do you know

10:15.991 --> 10:17.409
how lucky you are?

10:17.409 --> 10:20.704
- George, let him read the letter.

10:24.541 --> 10:26.001
- Over the past year,

10:27.044 --> 10:30.255
I've been followed
by multiple private investigators.

10:31.507 --> 10:33.425
I have been frightened for my safety.

10:34.843 --> 10:37.054
I've stopped seeing most of my friends.

10:37.971 --> 10:41.266
I've struggled... with depression.

10:42.559 --> 10:43.560
[sighs]

10:43.560 --> 10:46.438
My parents, your son
and daughter-in-law,

10:48.148 --> 10:49.942
almost had to sell their house

10:49.942 --> 10:52.653
to pay hundreds of thousands
of dollars in legal fees.

10:57.157 --> 10:58.992
And the only reasons I can think

10:58.992 --> 11:01.662
as to why you continue
to believe Elizabeth's lies--

11:01.662 --> 11:04.331
- You're the one who
just admitted to being a liar.

11:06.667 --> 11:09.086
- The only reasons
that make sense

11:09.878 --> 11:12.673
are that you are complicit
in what Theranos is doing--

11:12.673 --> 11:14.007
- Ridiculous!

11:15.717 --> 11:16.760
- Or--

11:18.303 --> 11:19.054
Um--

11:20.055 --> 11:21.139
- Or what?

11:23.809 --> 11:25.310
That I'm losing my mind?

11:29.189 --> 11:30.691
That I have dementia.

11:35.320 --> 11:36.488
- The only way

11:37.447 --> 11:41.660
that I believe our relationship
could be repaired at this point

11:44.204 --> 11:48.000
is if you stepped forward
as the first board member of Theranos

11:48.000 --> 11:50.752
to come out against Elizabeth
and her company.

11:53.714 --> 11:54.756
I--

11:58.802 --> 11:59.720
I love you.

12:01.471 --> 12:02.472
Tyler.

12:08.854 --> 12:10.272
- Get out of my home.

12:11.440 --> 12:15.027
♪

12:15.027 --> 12:19.156
♪

12:20.782 --> 12:22.201
- Thank-thank you for the tea.

12:24.995 --> 12:28.332
♪

12:44.348 --> 12:45.557
[sighs]

12:47.267 --> 12:49.311
- Jared Leto's presenting me
with the award.

12:51.480 --> 12:53.774
He's an actor.
- Oh, that's fun.

12:54.691 --> 12:56.193
So glamorous.

12:56.193 --> 12:57.819
[laughs]

13:00.948 --> 13:05.410
- Uh, thank you for--

13:06.495 --> 13:10.457
I just, I know it's been
a hard couple weeks,

13:11.500 --> 13:15.212
and I feel like you've just,
you've become a friend, Linda.

13:15.212 --> 13:16.296
So I think I--

13:17.172 --> 13:18.507
I don't have many friends, so--

13:21.635 --> 13:22.761
- Oh, well.

13:24.179 --> 13:27.641
♪

13:28.809 --> 13:29.935
GPS VOICE:
You have arrived.

13:31.186 --> 13:32.104
- Thank you.

13:37.276 --> 13:38.902
Hi, I'm Gary Yamamoto

13:38.902 --> 13:41.572
from the Centers for Medicare
and Medicaid Services.

13:41.572 --> 13:43.323
I'm here to inspect the labs.

13:43.323 --> 13:44.783
GPS VOICE:
You have arrived.

13:45.868 --> 13:47.244
Sorry.
[chuckles]

13:47.244 --> 13:49.037
I can't figure out
how to turn this thing off.

13:49.913 --> 13:51.164
Uhh--

13:51.164 --> 13:52.958
♪

13:55.419 --> 13:57.254
ELIZABETH: What is he eating?
Is that a snack?

13:57.254 --> 13:59.715
- I can't see.
- Is it, uh, is it fruit?

13:59.715 --> 14:00.757
ELIZABETH:
Is it grapes?

14:01.550 --> 14:02.718
- We have to show him the lab.

14:02.718 --> 14:05.304
We knew this could happen.
Maybe we can get away with a fine.

14:05.304 --> 14:06.889
- He can shut down the labs.

14:06.889 --> 14:09.057
- We don't know that yet.
- Who complained to CMS?

14:09.057 --> 14:10.726
Somebody had to have complained.

14:10.726 --> 14:13.061
Do you think it was Mark or Tyler?

14:13.061 --> 14:15.105
He just went on record
with Carreyrou.

14:15.105 --> 14:17.316
- I'll find out. I find out
and nail the motherfucker.

14:17.316 --> 14:19.860
I'm so sick and tired
of wasting time on this bullshit

14:19.860 --> 14:21.653
instead of on what really matters.

14:21.653 --> 14:24.615
- Yes, the products?
Yes. Yes.

14:24.615 --> 14:26.116
The rules are outdated.

14:26.116 --> 14:27.534
How can we actually get anything done?

14:27.534 --> 14:30.037
How can we make any changes
if we're being hunted?

14:30.829 --> 14:33.457
Hunted and harassed
by the government.

14:33.457 --> 14:36.251
Who's telling them what to do?
Quest, Labcorp?

14:36.251 --> 14:38.712
- Maybe. Maybe. Maybe.

14:38.712 --> 14:40.964
But we do have to talk
to him at some point.

14:40.964 --> 14:42.382
So what are we going to do?

14:43.008 --> 14:45.677
Who's going to sit with him?
- Um-- Um--

14:47.095 --> 14:48.889
Uh, one, one of us
should talk to him.

14:48.889 --> 14:50.849
- Oh, definitely, definitely.
- Yeah.

14:51.475 --> 14:52.601
- Or we go in together.

14:53.810 --> 14:55.812
- Y-yeah. Yeah, maybe.

14:55.812 --> 14:58.440
- Well, from a legal perspective,

14:58.440 --> 15:01.026
I, I think that we should
keep Elizabeth out of it.

15:02.319 --> 15:04.988
- Really?
Yeah, I mean, I-I-I--

15:05.656 --> 15:07.950
I'm not afraid
of, of talking to him

15:07.950 --> 15:10.702
or, you know, answering questions.

15:10.702 --> 15:12.913
- I don't think that you should.

15:12.913 --> 15:15.832
- Oh. Well.

15:16.375 --> 15:17.376
You can do it.

15:18.252 --> 15:19.253
- Alone?

15:19.253 --> 15:22.214
- Well, I have
that ceremony tonight,

15:22.214 --> 15:24.383
and I think that's going to be
really good for our image.

15:24.383 --> 15:25.425
- What's the award?

15:25.425 --> 15:27.553
- I'm one of the women
of the year.

15:28.637 --> 15:29.680
Yeah.

15:31.098 --> 15:32.516
I'm so lucky to have you.

15:33.350 --> 15:34.393
You can do this.

15:36.103 --> 15:37.771
Fight. Transcend.

15:38.564 --> 15:41.775
You knock the legs out from under him.
You run circles around him.

15:41.775 --> 15:44.027
You do the presentation.
You sell him on us.

15:44.736 --> 15:46.822
The PowerPoint. Everything.

15:48.407 --> 15:49.449
- No.

15:50.450 --> 15:51.410
- What do you mean?

15:51.410 --> 15:53.495
- I don't need to see
a presentation.

15:53.495 --> 15:55.831
I just need to see the labs.
Where's Elizabeth Holmes?

15:55.831 --> 15:59.209
- Well, I'd like to talk
to whoever it is you work for.

16:00.502 --> 16:02.713
We're going to talk to somebody. Linda.

16:02.713 --> 16:03.755
- Yes.

16:03.755 --> 16:05.883
We're going to contact
your superiors--

16:05.883 --> 16:07.467
- There's no one to talk to.

16:07.467 --> 16:09.678
I'll probably be holed up here
for a few days.

16:09.678 --> 16:10.971
I've got my checklist.

16:10.971 --> 16:13.765
I'll just work my way down the list
and write a report.

16:15.684 --> 16:17.436
- When is the report coming out?

16:17.436 --> 16:18.812
- You won't have to wait too long.

16:20.147 --> 16:24.776
♪ upbeat percussive music ♪

16:24.776 --> 16:28.280
♪

16:28.280 --> 16:30.199
- Holy shit!

16:30.199 --> 16:35.037
♪

16:51.386 --> 16:54.473
Two years.
They shut her down for two years.

16:54.473 --> 16:56.183
She won't come back from this.

16:56.183 --> 17:00.437
♪

17:00.437 --> 17:02.981
♪

17:02.981 --> 17:03.899
[laughs]

17:06.485 --> 17:08.487
- Go.
- Oh, I'm going to write it.

17:08.487 --> 17:09.446
- Yeah. Now.

17:09.446 --> 17:13.534
- Federal bureaucracy.
Red tape. It is beautiful.

17:13.534 --> 17:14.868
- Go write--
JOHN: It is slow

17:14.868 --> 17:16.995
and boring and beautiful.

17:16.995 --> 17:18.080
- Go. Go!

17:20.332 --> 17:22.626
- I just fell in love
with federal bureaucracy,

17:22.626 --> 17:24.169
and I don't care who knows it!

17:24.628 --> 17:25.838
[laughter]

17:37.057 --> 17:39.935
- This report is going
to come out.

17:41.770 --> 17:43.480
Somebody probably already leaked it.

17:45.482 --> 17:46.525
- Uh-huh.

17:48.527 --> 17:50.195
- We're going to have
to do something.

17:53.949 --> 17:55.450
I'm going to have to make a move.

18:18.724 --> 18:20.642
- Do you remember the first time
you spoke to me?

18:21.935 --> 18:23.020
In Beijing?

18:26.815 --> 18:28.108
I was just remembering.

18:31.278 --> 18:33.572
I was going back
over old emails,

18:34.323 --> 18:35.365
text messages.

18:38.368 --> 18:39.578
- Why would you do that?

18:40.579 --> 18:41.663
- I told you.

18:42.956 --> 18:44.124
I wanted to remember.

18:46.335 --> 18:47.336
- Why?

18:49.588 --> 18:50.839
- It's romantic

18:52.341 --> 18:54.092
to look over old texts.

18:57.346 --> 18:58.805
- Are you threatening me?

19:04.394 --> 19:06.188
Have you been speaking to a lawyer?

19:13.612 --> 19:14.780
- Yes.

19:16.198 --> 19:17.616
I called a lawyer.

19:22.955 --> 19:24.039
[inhales sharply]

19:26.500 --> 19:28.210
I have to protect myself.

19:30.921 --> 19:32.172
- From what?

19:33.966 --> 19:36.009
Do you think that we did
something wrong?

19:39.012 --> 19:41.849
Or did you do something
that I didn't know about?

19:43.892 --> 19:47.104
- You think that... I did things

19:47.104 --> 19:49.815
that you didn't do?

19:49.815 --> 19:51.066
- Did you?

19:52.776 --> 19:54.486
I don't know everything
that you did.

19:56.613 --> 19:58.782
If you did something wrong,

20:00.158 --> 20:01.618
you should tell me.

20:07.165 --> 20:08.876
What did you do, Sunny?

20:12.045 --> 20:13.380
Maybe I could help you.

20:14.756 --> 20:17.176
I could set you up
with some good lawyers.

20:23.223 --> 20:26.268
- So... I'm taking the blame?

20:30.063 --> 20:31.440
I'm taking the blame?

20:35.569 --> 20:38.697
I worked for six years

20:38.697 --> 20:41.366
day and night to help you.

20:45.204 --> 20:46.538
This was your dream.

20:48.123 --> 20:49.208
Your passion.

20:50.542 --> 20:51.668
Not mine.

20:53.045 --> 20:55.631
- I know how hard it's going
to be to transition.

20:56.924 --> 20:59.718
- Transition? [scoffs]
- Transition out of the company.

21:01.637 --> 21:05.098
But you should know
that I am so grateful to you

21:06.099 --> 21:07.893
for everything that you've done.

21:11.438 --> 21:13.482
You've known me since I was a girl.

21:15.359 --> 21:17.152
How old was I when,
when I met you?

21:18.737 --> 21:22.115
I was... barely 18.

21:25.702 --> 21:27.287
You've taught me everything I know.

21:30.457 --> 21:31.875
- You are good.

21:32.626 --> 21:34.253
- So I just want you to know that

21:35.838 --> 21:41.468
this is going to be really hard
for me to handle... emotionally.

21:51.019 --> 21:53.021
- I'm not leaving
until we break even.

21:54.690 --> 21:56.191
We'll do this together.

21:56.942 --> 21:59.528
And I will be by your side
until the end.

22:04.867 --> 22:07.327
I can't leave like this.
I, I can't.

22:10.163 --> 22:12.249
We will talk and find

22:12.249 --> 22:16.670
the perfect focus
and... perfect plan.

22:18.297 --> 22:20.132
And we'll execute
with our heads down

22:20.132 --> 22:22.801
and build a new product
and break even.

22:22.801 --> 22:24.261
ELIZABETH:
Yeah.

22:27.055 --> 22:28.765
- You need me until then.

22:30.893 --> 22:32.603
We're tied together.

22:34.771 --> 22:35.898
- Of course.

23:02.216 --> 23:03.634
- But where will you live?

23:07.679 --> 23:08.972
- What do you mean?

23:10.974 --> 23:12.476
- The house is in my name.

23:15.479 --> 23:20.192
[cell phone ringing]

23:28.534 --> 23:30.369
- Hello.
- It's John.

23:32.287 --> 23:35.457
I just wanted to let you know

23:35.457 --> 23:38.168
that... I just got word

23:38.168 --> 23:40.671
that CMS is shutting down
the Theranos labs.

23:41.505 --> 23:43.841
- Wait, what?
JOHN: For two years.

23:47.886 --> 23:49.513
Erika, did you hear me?

23:50.931 --> 23:52.891
I want to make sure
that you know that

23:54.977 --> 23:56.353
this is happening because of you.

23:56.353 --> 23:59.439
Because of the letter that you wrote.

23:59.439 --> 24:02.442
And... I know

24:03.235 --> 24:06.738
what it took
to sign your name and--

24:06.738 --> 24:08.073
Actually, I don't.

24:09.908 --> 24:11.118
But, uh,

24:12.119 --> 24:13.912
you saved people's lives.

24:18.083 --> 24:19.376
Erika, are you there?

24:27.050 --> 24:29.094
- Um, I probably,

24:29.094 --> 24:31.221
I shouldn't be talking to you
on the phone right now but

24:36.226 --> 24:37.352
thank you.

24:42.983 --> 24:44.484
[sobs, sniffles]

24:52.534 --> 24:55.537
[phones ringing, office chatter]

24:57.623 --> 25:02.002
♪

25:02.002 --> 25:05.964
♪

25:05.964 --> 25:09.968
♪

25:16.308 --> 25:17.726
MAN:
Yeah.

25:18.977 --> 25:22.481
♪

25:34.785 --> 25:37.996
♪

25:41.750 --> 25:43.210
- Hello, Miriam.

25:43.210 --> 25:45.796
- Who's Miriam? That's not my name.

25:45.796 --> 25:47.339
- Do you know where Elizabeth is?

25:47.339 --> 25:50.175
- I thought you knew she went home
right after the board meeting.

25:50.843 --> 25:53.679
- What board meeting?
It's seven o'clock in the morning.

25:53.679 --> 25:56.431
- She said to let you sleep,
that she would catch you up.

25:58.517 --> 26:03.564
♪

26:03.564 --> 26:06.149
[indistinct chatter]

26:09.987 --> 26:11.488
- I respect your decision.

26:12.990 --> 26:14.908
- My decision?
- To step down.

26:15.534 --> 26:17.536
It's the right thing to do for Elizabeth.

26:26.670 --> 26:29.131
LAWYER: What is your current relationship
with Sunny Balwani?

26:29.756 --> 26:31.633
ELIZABETH: We haven't talked
in a long time.

26:32.676 --> 26:34.553
LAWYER: What happened
to the relationship?

26:34.553 --> 26:36.847
ELIZABETH: What do you mean?
LAWYER: How did it end?

26:36.847 --> 26:38.974
- The personal relationship?
LAWYER: Yes.

26:39.975 --> 26:41.101
SUNNY:
Elizabeth!

26:42.227 --> 26:43.103
Elizabeth!

26:43.103 --> 26:45.189
- You know, I, I think
when he joined the company,

26:47.649 --> 26:51.445
it was-- when we started
working together,

26:51.445 --> 26:54.448
It was a very intense
working relationship.

26:56.200 --> 27:00.162
And there, this sort of
romantic piece that was there

27:00.162 --> 27:01.496
in the beginning died.

27:05.292 --> 27:09.213
I, I don't think it happened in,
in one moment.

27:09.213 --> 27:11.298
I, I think it just
became clear that

27:12.508 --> 27:13.926
that we were colleagues.

27:15.511 --> 27:18.013
LAWYER: Mr. Balwani is no longer
at Theranos, correct?

27:18.555 --> 27:20.807
- That's right.
LAWYER: Why did he leave?

27:22.142 --> 27:23.560
- It was time for new leadership

27:23.560 --> 27:27.397
and, um, a different leadership structure.

27:28.565 --> 27:30.651
LAWYER: Was it mutual?
- Yes.

27:31.151 --> 27:32.569
SUNNY:
Elizabeth!

27:32.569 --> 27:33.654
Elizabeth!

27:33.654 --> 27:34.947
ELIZABETH: In here.
- Elizabeth!

27:36.740 --> 27:37.950
You bitch.

27:39.076 --> 27:41.119
You bitch.
- What are you going to do?

27:42.246 --> 27:44.706
You said you would step down
from my company, so you're stepping down.

27:44.706 --> 27:47.000
- I said on my terms!

27:47.000 --> 27:48.085
I said on my terms.

27:48.085 --> 27:49.586
When we broke even.

27:49.586 --> 27:52.089
What is this? What is this?
- I'm leaving-- I'm leaving you.

27:52.089 --> 27:53.215
- Now you're leaving me?

27:53.215 --> 27:56.134
- You said the house was in your name.
- So you go and run away behind my back?

27:56.134 --> 27:57.135
- I'm going to get my own place.

27:57.135 --> 27:58.804
- This is how you treat
someone who loves you?

27:58.804 --> 28:00.514
Who's loved you for years?

28:02.641 --> 28:03.851
Oh my god.

28:03.851 --> 28:05.435
- I'm going to take a few
of my things now.

28:05.435 --> 28:07.771
- There's nothing there.
- And someone I trust is gonna--

28:07.771 --> 28:09.356
- There's nothing inside you.

28:10.440 --> 28:12.234
I invented you inside my head.

28:12.234 --> 28:14.820
For 12 years, I've been inventing you.
I made you up.

28:15.487 --> 28:16.697
You're not real!

28:18.824 --> 28:20.617
You don't have feelings!

28:21.243 --> 28:22.703
You aren't a person.

28:22.703 --> 28:24.121
You're a ghost.

28:25.080 --> 28:27.207
You're nothing.
You're nothing!

28:29.042 --> 28:30.210
You're not real.

28:33.130 --> 28:34.381
You're nothing.

28:34.381 --> 28:36.383
- And you're a mediocre
software engineer.

28:36.884 --> 28:38.302
[clattering]

28:39.803 --> 28:41.263
- Okay, bye.

28:48.228 --> 28:49.104
[car door closes]

28:54.943 --> 28:58.530
- You think you can
get rid of me and carry on?

28:59.698 --> 29:00.824
It's over.

29:01.408 --> 29:03.076
They're going to come for us.

29:04.369 --> 29:06.788
We could go to jail.
- I have a lot of lawyers.

29:06.788 --> 29:08.373
- You have no idea
what's about to happen.

29:09.833 --> 29:12.503
Trust me, the world is a mean place.

29:13.837 --> 29:16.507
Everyone has only been nice to you
because of greed.

29:17.591 --> 29:19.927
They won't stay.
They'll leave you.

29:20.761 --> 29:22.137
Everyone will leave you.

29:22.137 --> 29:24.139
And they'll say
they didn't know anything.

29:24.139 --> 29:25.724
- And what are you going to say?

29:29.645 --> 29:31.146
- I won't hurt you.

29:39.863 --> 29:40.906
[sighs]

29:44.284 --> 29:45.160
[car beeps]

30:15.524 --> 30:18.068
NOEL HOLMES:
Can you touch this part up some?

30:18.068 --> 30:20.696
It's looking a little
[winces] dead.

30:20.696 --> 30:23.991
- Did you know almost five million people
watch his show every morning?

30:23.991 --> 30:25.409
I had no idea.
- Chris.

30:25.409 --> 30:26.869
- What?
- You know, I don't need you.

30:26.869 --> 30:29.246
I, I can do this.
CHRIS: It's impressive.

30:29.246 --> 30:31.039
- The lawyer said
your brother might get deposed.

30:31.039 --> 30:32.499
Is that true, Elizabeth?

30:32.499 --> 30:33.917
- I don't know yet.

30:33.917 --> 30:35.794
CHRIS HOLMES:
And you got rid of Sunny.

30:35.794 --> 30:38.422
I had no idea he was mismanaging
the lab so badly.

30:38.422 --> 30:41.508
- Hi. Just coming in
to wish you good luck.

30:41.508 --> 30:44.720
- Well, that's great. You know,
we were just talking about Sunny.

30:44.720 --> 30:46.513
How glad we are that he's gone.

30:46.513 --> 30:47.639
- Yes.

30:48.307 --> 30:51.435
Well, Linda has been over
the talking points.

30:51.435 --> 30:54.479
Now this interviewer will be
very hard on you,

30:54.479 --> 30:57.983
but that's your opportunity
to apologize.

30:57.983 --> 31:01.445
- Yes, apologize. And then
she can just move on from this.

31:01.445 --> 31:02.404
- Absolutely.

31:02.404 --> 31:05.824
Own up to the mistakes Sunny made
and then talk about

31:05.824 --> 31:07.784
how you're going to move
the company forward.

31:08.535 --> 31:10.996
- And we've gone over
the wording of the apology

31:10.996 --> 31:13.540
and we feel good about it.

31:16.210 --> 31:18.170
- Yes, well,
this is going to be great.

31:18.170 --> 31:22.257
We're behind you, and they have set up
that conference room with a live feed

31:22.257 --> 31:24.510
so we can watch.
Is your makeup done?

31:26.887 --> 31:28.096
You look different.

31:31.141 --> 31:33.852
- You know, I'm just, I'll, I'll get
someone to touch it up, yeah.

31:35.437 --> 31:36.855
So, how are you doing?

31:38.357 --> 31:42.694
Did you have a chance to look
at the apology that we drafted?

31:42.694 --> 31:46.615
- Yeah. Yeah.
- I don't work in PR, but, uh, I think,

31:46.615 --> 31:48.700
I think what people want right now

31:48.700 --> 31:50.953
is some acknowledgment, right?

31:50.953 --> 31:52.788
Some emotional acknowledgment.

31:52.788 --> 31:55.916
So, uh... like...

31:56.834 --> 31:59.795
they want to know that,
that you're ashamed, you know.

31:59.795 --> 32:01.004
- Ashamed?

32:01.004 --> 32:03.966
- Especially in that word,
uh, "devastated."

32:03.966 --> 32:06.760
Keep it really warm.
Really sincere.

32:10.848 --> 32:12.182
Well, it looks like they're ready.

32:12.182 --> 32:15.060
So, you know, you know what,
just don't even overthink it.

32:15.519 --> 32:18.313
At all. Just go be yourself.

32:23.652 --> 32:26.864
- The Centers for Medicare and Medicaid
have shut down your lab.

32:28.240 --> 32:29.491
- One lab.

32:30.158 --> 32:33.662
- Okay, but that is
a pretty big obstacle

32:33.662 --> 32:37.040
for a medical company
that's been valued at over $9 billion.

32:37.040 --> 32:38.834
ELIZABETH: [on TV]
It wouldn't be the first time

32:38.834 --> 32:41.712
that we've bounced back from a challenge.

32:42.212 --> 32:45.424
INTERVIEWER: To be frank, this seems
like more than just a challenge.

32:45.424 --> 32:49.344
CMS found critical violations
throughout the laboratory.

32:49.344 --> 32:53.015
In fact, they say that
the lab posed immediate jeopardy

32:53.015 --> 32:54.516
to patient safety.

32:58.145 --> 33:00.397
What's your response to that?

33:02.900 --> 33:04.484
- I feel devastated

33:05.235 --> 33:09.573
that we didn't catch
and fix the issue faster.

33:10.240 --> 33:11.658
INTERVIEWER:
Do you hold yourself responsible

33:11.658 --> 33:14.369
for not hiring the right people,

33:14.369 --> 33:16.288
for not having critical oversight?

33:17.456 --> 33:19.208
- Like I said, I feel devastated.

33:20.417 --> 33:25.380
Uh, and we're looking
to rebuild from scratch.

33:25.380 --> 33:27.841
I'm, I'm a better leader now,

33:27.841 --> 33:31.178
and like I said, it's devastating.

33:34.681 --> 33:36.642
INTERVIEWER: You're running
a healthcare startup.

33:36.642 --> 33:38.977
You're dealing with people's lives.

33:38.977 --> 33:40.729
You're dealing with test results

33:40.729 --> 33:43.815
that doctors use
to diagnose their patients.

33:43.815 --> 33:46.985
So you would have thought
that you would have

33:46.985 --> 33:49.446
lab integrity in place
from the get-go.

33:51.365 --> 33:52.449
- Yeah.

33:54.243 --> 33:55.327
Yeah.

33:58.372 --> 34:01.667
Like I said... it's devastating.

34:01.667 --> 34:03.085
Absolutely.

34:04.211 --> 34:06.922
But I, I believe that, that--

34:08.549 --> 34:11.301
I don't believe that we put
anyone's health in danger.

34:13.011 --> 34:15.681
♪

34:15.681 --> 34:19.685
♪

34:23.146 --> 34:24.648
CHARLOTTE SCHULTZ:
You ready to go?

34:24.648 --> 34:27.317
It's cold. I think you may need
a jacket or something.

34:28.986 --> 34:30.195
George?

34:33.782 --> 34:34.867
George.

34:38.787 --> 34:42.040
[quiet murmuring]

34:48.672 --> 34:54.344
♪

34:54.344 --> 34:57.389
- Where is everybody? Where's David?
LINDA: Oh, they just, um--

34:57.389 --> 34:59.933
That was good.
Tha-that was a good job.

35:00.767 --> 35:04.521
I'm just going
to follow up on, on a few--

35:10.360 --> 35:13.197
- You looked great!

35:13.197 --> 35:15.240
- It was a good start.

35:15.240 --> 35:16.700
- Oh, leave me alone.

35:18.285 --> 35:20.162
- Don't talk to us like that.

35:20.162 --> 35:22.372
- Chris, she needs
to change her clothes.

35:23.790 --> 35:24.750
[sighs]

35:26.251 --> 35:27.753
Right.
[clears throat]

35:34.843 --> 35:36.803
You're going to rebuild.

35:39.640 --> 35:40.682
You will.

35:41.350 --> 35:43.268
NOEL: You're just smearing it in.
Give it to me.

35:44.853 --> 35:47.272
I think I'm very angry at you.
I am.

35:47.981 --> 35:49.191
I'm very angry.

35:52.152 --> 35:54.863
- You told me that,
when you visited me at school,

35:55.864 --> 35:57.908
after everything that happened,

35:57.908 --> 36:02.287
you told me to just put it away

36:02.287 --> 36:04.748
and... forget it.

36:07.835 --> 36:10.921
If you choose to forget certain things,

36:12.256 --> 36:13.966
do you think that's lying?

36:19.221 --> 36:20.597
- I'll be outside.

36:21.682 --> 36:23.183
I don't understand.

36:24.935 --> 36:25.978
[sniffles]

36:25.978 --> 36:29.982
♪

36:49.459 --> 36:50.502
[sighs]

36:50.502 --> 36:55.257
♪

37:04.183 --> 37:05.267
[exhales]

37:20.199 --> 37:21.450
MAN: [whispers]
Lizzie.

37:23.410 --> 37:24.494
Lizzie.

37:28.332 --> 37:29.833
I knew it.

37:30.375 --> 37:32.127
[laughing] You were faking it.

37:32.127 --> 37:34.671
- I was asleep.
- Liar.

37:34.671 --> 37:36.381
Dude, you're a liar.

37:36.381 --> 37:38.258
[both chuckle]

37:39.760 --> 37:40.928
Oh, I love you.

37:41.637 --> 37:42.930
- I love you too.

37:42.930 --> 37:46.475
- Exhibit 264 purports to be

37:46.475 --> 37:48.769
a September 23, 2014, email

37:48.769 --> 37:50.896
from Elizabeth Holmes to Sunny Balwani

37:50.896 --> 37:53.982
with subject line
"Re: Innovation payment letter."

37:54.650 --> 37:57.236
Have you seen exhibit 264 before?

37:57.236 --> 38:01.156
- I don't remember, but I have
no reason to doubt the email.

38:02.324 --> 38:04.201
MAN:
You just got to give me, like, one,

38:04.201 --> 38:07.037
one item of food.

38:07.037 --> 38:08.997
Anything.
- I, I don't know.

38:08.997 --> 38:10.249
MAN:
How do you not know?

38:10.249 --> 38:12.292
- I don't.
MAN: Favorite food!

38:12.292 --> 38:15.337
- Did Mr. Balwani provide
financial projections to investors?

38:15.337 --> 38:18.882
- I can't remember
specific instances sitting here.

38:18.882 --> 38:20.259
MAN:
There's these wind storms,

38:20.259 --> 38:22.803
and you have to wear goggles
because it's so fucking dusty.

38:23.262 --> 38:26.890
But like, you just feel
so much love in the air.

38:27.349 --> 38:30.394
And then at the end,
they burn this 60-foot,

38:30.394 --> 38:33.605
like, wooden structure
of a man and--

38:34.189 --> 38:35.482
But it's just like

38:35.983 --> 38:39.278
all your fears
and your inhibitions, they just--

38:40.279 --> 38:43.448
Like, everything goes up
in, like, a big fire.

38:44.324 --> 38:46.451
And it's just
so fucking cleansing.

38:46.451 --> 38:47.870
- You're beautiful.

38:49.538 --> 38:50.998
- You're beautiful.

